# Solo IT Time Management Rule

## Session Start Protocol
- Start by checking latest files in `vedant/todo/` and `vedant/learner/`.
- Summarize: top 3 priorities, top 3 risks, blockers, and backlog delta.
- If no daily file exists for today, create files only on Monday-Friday:
  - `vedant/todo/YYYY-MM-DD.md`
  - `vedant/learner/YYYY-MM-DD.md`
- On Saturday or Sunday, do not create a normal daily file unless explicitly requested.
- Weekend default mode: optional light review only (no full sprint load).
- This rule is persistent and recurring: repeat this cycle every workday without expiration.

## Task Definition Standard
- Every task must include: impact, estimate, deadline, owner (`you` or `agent`), and status.
- Use statuses only: `todo`, `in_progress`, `blocked`, `done`, `dropped`.
- If blocked for more than 1 day, add escalation action and owner.
- Every P1/P2 task must include formality metadata: requirement ID, test evidence, and release decision.

## Daily Execution Discipline
- Plan using 3 focus blocks only (high-value tasks first).
- Keep work in progress <= 3 items.
- End of day must include: done list, not-done list, carry-forward, and tomorrow first task.
- Office schedule baseline: Monday-Friday execution days.
- Do not mark work `done` without evidence link (PR, commit, test output, or deployment log).

## Backlog and Timeline Control
- Keep one source of truth: `vedant/todo/backlog.md`.
- Every completed daily file must update backlog item status.
- Weekly review must identify overdue items and split oversized tasks.
- Every feature must map to a sprint/milestone and production readiness gate.
- Maintain release forecast for next 2 sprints and highlight at-risk items.

## Production Readiness Gate (Before Live)
- Required checks: tests pass, lint pass, rollback plan, monitoring, and risk notes.
- Track DORA baseline for each release: deployment frequency, lead time, change failure rate, MTTR.
- Track security baseline: secrets handling, dependency scan, vulnerability response owner/date.
- Use staged release flow: `dev -> staging -> production`.
- Require post-release verification window and go/no-go confirmation.

## Mandatory Formalities (Enterprise-style)
- Keep requirement artifacts: PRD/user story + acceptance criteria.
- Keep decision artifacts: ADR for major technical decisions.
- Keep delivery artifacts: change record, release checklist, incident log.
- Keep review artifacts: weekly review notes and monthly audit notes.

## Non-Negotiable Don'ts
- Do not start coding before writing today priorities and constraints.
- Do not run unplanned tasks unless marked as urgent and logged in backlog delta.
- Do not close day without carry-forward and blocker status updates.
- Do not deploy directly to production without staging validation.
- Do not close incidents without root-cause note and prevention action.
